#commonportsandprotocols

April 13, 2026

Having built a solid understanding of how devices receive their network identities (IP Addressing & DHCP) and how we find them using human-readable names (DNS), 
the next critical piece of the puzzle is understanding how they actually communicate. I am dedicating this log to Ports and Protocols.

Port: A logical connection (not physical) that identifies a specific process or service running on a computer/server. Ports determine what programs and services will be used by the 
computer/server. Ports are associated with an IP address and both work together to exchange data on a network; IP address gets data to the device, Ports ensure they reach the correct
application. Together they form a Socket.

Ports have unique numbers that identify them ranging from 0 - 65,535 assigned by IANA (Internet Assigned Numbers Authority) .This range is then split even further into 3 categories 
as follows:
  0-1023 System/Well-Known Ports: These are ports that are common and are used by people every single day. These ports are considered the most "open" and are the most strictly 
  monitored by IANA. 
    Examples:
      Port 21 (FTP | File Transfer Protocol): Port 21 is the primary control channel for FTP (File Transfer Protocol), used to send commands like "login," "list," and "download" 
      between a client and a server. It works in tandem with Port 20, which handles the actual transfer of the data bits. Because it transmits credentials in plain text, it is 
      considered insecure and has largely been replaced by SFTP (Port 22) in modern IT environments.
  
      Port 25 (SMTP | Simple Mail Transfer Protocol): The standard port used for transferring email between mail servers (relaying). While it is the backbone of email delivery, it is 
      often blocked on residential networks and by firewalls to prevent spam, with encrypted ports like 587 preferred for end-user email submission.
  
      Port 53 (DNS | Domain Name System): The port dedicated to the Domain Name System. It translates human-readable domain names into IP addresses. It primarily uses UDP for fast 
      client queries but switches to TCP for zone transfers or when data exceeds the size limit of a standard UDP packet.
  
      Port 67 (DHCP | Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol): Port 67 (DHCP Server): The destination port used by DHCP servers to receive requests from clients. It works along with 
      Port 68 (client-side) to facilitate the automatic assignment of IP addresses, subnet masks, and default gateways using the UDP protocol.
  
      Port 443 (HTTPS | Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure): The standard port for secure, encrypted web traffic. It utilizes SSL/TLS to encrypt communications between a web browser 
      and a server, ensuring data privacy and integrity. It is the secure successor to Port 80 and is the backbone of modern secure internet communication.
  
  
  1024-49151 User/Registered Ports: These are typically used for non-core system processes like database communication (SQL), remote desktop (RDP), and VoIP. They do not usually 
  require administrative privileges to use on a client machine but are critical for firewall configuration.
    Examples:
      Port 1433 (MS SQL Server): This is the software engine powering many different corporate/company applications such as payroll systems or customer data bases. To exchange
      data securely between different apps and the database system, TCP is used.

      Port 1812 (RADIUS | Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service): This is the main Port utilized for network authentication. Used as centralized management for anyone trying to
      connect to a network service like company Wi-Fi or a VPN. UDP is used to ensure speed and is the backbone behind secure per-user access control in company environments.

      Port 3389 (RDP | Remote Desktop Protocol): This is the default Port for Microsoft's Desktop Control. It provides the a GUI (Graphical User Interface) for remote management
      of Windows-based systems. This is a very commonly attacked port so it typically only has internal access or requires a VPN to access.

      Port 5060 (SIP | Session Initiation Protocol): This is thw default port that is used in SIP to be able to be used in VoIP systems. It manages call signaling, such as initiating, 
      maintaining, and terminating voice or video calls. While 5060 is unencrypted, Port 5061 is used for secure, encrypted SIP (SIPS).

      Port 8080 (Port 80 Alternative): This is commonly seen as the Port 80 (HTTP) backup port, or the HTTP Alternate. It's essentially a "test" version of Port 80. It is frequently 
      utilized for web proxy services, caching, or for running secondary web applications on a single server.
  
